<PilotConstants>
   <!-- GLOBAL NOTES:

	I. All data entered in this file should be within <entry> elements.
	
	II. <entry> elements have exactly three attributes:
	
		1. name, which is case-sensitive and should never change
		
		2. type, which can be "int", "float", "string", or "int=string"
		
		3. value, which can contain 1 to many comma-delimitted values.
			"int=string" values must contain an integer, followed by an
			equals sign, followed by a string.  Strings cannot contain
			equals signs or commas, and only internal whitespace will
			be preserved.  leading and trailing whitespace will be
			trimmed.
	
	III. "int=string" type entries are often used to name particular
		sub-ranges within a larger range of values.  To interpret such
		an entry, a particular named sub-range starts at the value given
		for that name and ends 1 before the value for the next name.  For
		example, if the entry is:
		
			<entry name="Example" type="int=string"
				value="50=first,120=second,500=third" />
		
		Then for a value x, its sub-range is the one that satisfies the
		corresponding equation in the following table:
		
			 50 <= x < 120,  first
			120 <= x < 500,  second
			500 <= x,        third
		
		Note that if x is less than the first value listed, its sub-range
		is undefined.	
	-->
